subSubSection.paragraph:
Skeleton ( Figs 20 e–g). As usual for the subgenus, the skeleton consists of a reticulation of spongin-encased spicule tracts. In this species, the spongin is often almost entirely obscured by the solid mass of the mycalostyles. Meshes are square, 1–2 mm wide, with primary tracts 200–300 µm in diameter and secondary tracts of 10–100 µm anastomosing at right angles. Microscleres common, anisochelae arranged in rosettes (
Fig. 20g
) of up to 65 µm in diameter.
